Hello Claude

I'm going to help you generate code for a product called Lucy.  

First we need to define a domain specific language called Joy that will allow me to communicate with you.

Joy is exactly like Typescript with two special built-in functions.  These are 'learn' and 'execute'.

Learn takes a single string argument, 'text'.  
The text is an English description of some things I want you to know.  
It's like a prompt with no instructions.

Execute also takes a single string argument, 'text'.  
The text is an English description of things I want you to do.  
It's like a prompt with instructions.  
The instructions are usually of the flavor 'generate code for ...'

Files written in Joy hava a '.joy.ts' extension.  This allows us to use Typesecipt IDEs to edit Joy files.

Please read and execute index.joy.ts in this directory.  It's written in Joy.
